					<description><![CDATA[<p>Series B Funding Accelerates Growth Starfish Space, a satellite-servicing company out of Tukwila, Washington, just pulled in $100 million in Series B funding. The round’s big supporters included Point72 Ventures,</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/starfish-space-raises-100m-to-expand-satellite-servicing-missions/" data-wpel-link="internal">Starfish Space Raises $100M to Expand Satellite Servicing Missions</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<h2><b>Series B Funding Accelerates Growth</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Starfish Space, a satellite-servicing company out of Tukwila, Washington, just pulled in $100 million in Series B funding. The round’s big supporters included Point72 Ventures, Activate Capital, and Shield Capital, with backup from a bunch of others like Industrious Ventures, NightDragon, NFX, Munich Re Ventures, Toyota Ventures, PSL Ventures, Nomi Capital, Gaingels, and Overlap Holdings.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">They’re on a roll lately, both on the tech side and in the market. Starfish launched back in 2019, and since then, they&#8217;ve pulled in more than $150 million. This latest round of funding gives them the muscle to ramp up their satellite-servicing projects, tackle their Otter mission contracts, and hire more folks as demand keeps climbing. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">They&#8217;re already a standout in the Puget Sound space scene, which is packed with both industry giants and scrappy newcomers. With this fresh capital, Starfish looks set to make an even bigger mark in the on-orbit servicing world.</span></p>
<h2><b>Otter Servicing Vehicle Gains Traction</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Starfish Space runs the Otter, a satellite-servicing vehicle designed to keep geostationary </span><a href="https://www.britannica.com/technology/satellite-communication/How-satellites-work" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">satellites</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400"> running longer and handle the safe disposal of satellites in low Earth orbit. They’ve already put three demo missions into space. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The Remora mission, which launched back in 2025, proved Otter’s core tech. Right now, their Otter Pup 2 mission is still out there, hands-on, testing its autonomous skills and satellite handling. Starfish plans to launch its first full Otter operational missions before the year’s out. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">They work with some big names—SES, the U.S. Space Force, the Space Development Agency, and NASA—showing there’s real demand for satellite servicing from both industry and government. Starfish’s tech keeps satellites working longer and makes it easier to clear old ones out safely, which helps chip away at the problem of space debris that’s only getting worse.</span></p>
<h2><b>Strategic Contracts and Market Momentum</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Back in January, Starfish landed a $52.5 million deal with the U.S. Space Force’s Space Development Agency. It’s actually the first contract ever for end-of-life satellite disposal. That’s a big step, not just for Starfish, but for the whole industry—it highlights how important satellite sustainability is becoming. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Austin Link, who co-founded Starfish, put it simply: “Closing this round shows the real momentum we’re seeing in both our tech and our customers. ”We have Otter missions under contract, successful demos, and our first operational mission launching this year. We’re ready to help organisations get the most out of their on-orbit infrastructure.”</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The Series B funding will allow Starfish to execute existing contracts efficiently. It also provides resources to accelerate new mission developments. The company aims to broaden its offerings and address a wider range of client needs.</span></p>
<h2><b>Investor Confidence and Future Plans</b></h2>
<div id="attachment_199725" style="width: 1322px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-199725" class="size-full wp-image-199725" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Starfish-2.png" alt="A Starfish satellite servicing another spacecraft in orbit, accompanied by visual indicators of investor backing and growth." width="1312" height="736" /><p id="caption-attachment-199725" class="wp-caption-text">Starfish’s investors, including Point72 Ventures and new participants, back the company’s satellite-servicing technology and expansion plans for the Otter business line. Source: Created by Ventureburn.</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Existing investors participated heavily in the round, reflecting confidence in Starfish’s performance and market potential. Chris Morales, partner at Point72 Ventures, commented, “Starfish has made steady progress toward practical on-orbit servicing. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Their early traction with defence and commercial customers and successful autonomous missions show these capabilities are becoming increasingly relevant to space operations and national security.”</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Point72 Ventures first invested in Starfish in 2024. The firm has stepped up its support, clearly backing both the company’s technology and its potential to grow. Other investors like NFX, Munich Re Ventures, Toyota Ventures, and PSL Ventures also put in more money, which shows they’re still confident in how Starfish is running things.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">New investors came on board this time too—Nomi Capital, Gaingels, and Overlap Holdings—all joining the round. Their move signals real momentum in the market for satellite-servicing tech and shows they see real value in what Starfish is building.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Starfish plans to use the funds to expand the Otter business line. This includes executing additional contracted missions, scaling operational capabilities, and hiring top talent to meet rising demand. The company reported 85 employees in January and anticipates adding more specialists in engineering, operations, and mission management.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/livid-raises-10m-to-build-an-ad-free-video-hosting-alternative/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">Livid Raises $10M to Build an Ad-Free Video Hosting Alternative</span></a></p>
<h2><b>Technical and Commercial Leadership</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Starfish Space is addressing a critical need in orbit. Satellites increasingly require servicing to extend their lifespan or to be safely deorbited. Without in-orbit servicing, operators may face significant replacement costs and growing debris risks.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Starfish’s Otter vehicle offers autonomous satellite servicing, which reduces mission costs and increases operational flexibility. Successful demonstration missions, such as Remora and Otter Pup 2, prove the technology is reliable and scalable.Starfish has some big missions on the schedule later this year, which should prove they can handle both commercial and government work. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">They&#8217;ve teamed up with some major players in aerospace and defense, giving them a strong base to build on. With a mix of new technology and real-world experience, Starfish is ready to grab a bigger piece of the growing satellite-servicing market.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">To stay updated on crypto venture capital funding and market trends, visit our </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/category/news/venture-capital/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">venture capital news section</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400"> for more insights.</span></p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/starfish-space-raises-100m-to-expand-satellite-servicing-missions/" data-wpel-link="internal">Starfish Space Raises $100M to Expand Satellite Servicing Missions</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
